1

00:00:02,440  -->  00:00:04,565
In this case study,

2

00:00:04,565  -->  00:00:10,090
you'll be analyzing AB test results for an online education company called Audacity,

3

00:00:10,090  -->  00:00:13,805
that offers courses on finance.

4

00:00:13,805  -->  00:00:18,379
Let's first see what a typical user flow might look like on Audacity site.

5

00:00:18,379  -->  00:00:21,123
New users would land on the home page,

6

00:00:21,123  -->  00:00:22,639
and if they're interested,

7

00:00:22,639  -->  00:00:24,860
they would click to explore courses.

8

00:00:24,860  -->  00:00:26,959
As they browse the course list,

9

00:00:26,959  -->  00:00:28,505
a course may catch their eye,

10

00:00:28,505  -->  00:00:30,805
and they click on it to learn more.

11

00:00:30,805  -->  00:00:32,900
Once they're on the course overview page,

12

00:00:32,900  -->  00:00:34,814
they may decide to enroll.

13

00:00:34,814  -->  00:00:37,835
After enrolling, they'd hopefully complete the course.

14

00:00:37,835  -->  00:00:40,995
In this flow, commonly called the customer funnel,

15

00:00:40,995  -->  00:00:44,825
users lose interest, and leave at different stages of the funnel,

16

00:00:44,825  -->  00:00:46,800
and few make it to the end.

17

00:00:46,800  -->  00:00:48,905
Of course, this is a simplistic model,

18

00:00:48,905  -->  00:00:51,825
and isn't how all user experiences would play out.

19

00:00:51,825  -->  00:00:54,620
But it does capture pretty well the main steps from

20

00:00:54,620  -->  00:00:59,300
an initial exposure to course completion in order of decreasing probability.

21

00:00:59,300  -->  00:01:01,610
To increase student engagement,

22

00:01:01,610  -->  00:01:05,225
Audacity wants to perform AB tests to try out changes,

23

00:01:05,225  -->  00:01:07,460
at different points in this funnel.

24

00:01:07,460  -->  00:01:08,685
In this case study,

25

00:01:08,685  -->  00:01:12,605
we'll analyze test results for two particular changes they have in mind,

26

00:01:12,605  -->  00:01:17,490
and then make a recommendation on whether they should launch each change.
